%N A395466 Decimal expansion of the area of the constructible squarable lune whose circular arcs have central angles in a 3:2 ratio and common chord of unit length.
%C A395466 One of the five constructible squarable lunes. It was discovered by Hippocrates of Chios in the 5th century BC.
%C A395466 Called the "concave pentagon lune" by Shelburne (2005).
%C A395466 See A395465 for details, references and more links.
%H A395466 Amiram Eldar, <a href="/A395466/a395466.png">Illustration</a>.
%H A395466 Mikhail Mikhailovich Postnikov, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2589121">The Problem of Squarable Lunes</a>, The American Mathematical Monthly, Vol. 107, No. 7 (2000), pp. 645-651. Translated from Russian by Abe Shenitzer.
%H A395466 Brian J. Shelburne, <a href="https://bshelburne.wittenberguniversity.org/TheFiveLunes120408.pdf">The Five Quadrable (Squarable) Lunes</a>, Wittenberg University Springfield, 2005.
%H A395466 <a href="/index/Al#algebraic_04">Index entries for algebraic numbers, degree 4</a>.
%F A395466 Equals sqrt((69 - 11*sqrt(33))/2)/12.
%F A395466 Equals f(3*theta) - f(2*theta), where theta = A395470, and f(x) = x/sin(x)^2 - cot(x)/4.
%F A395466 Minimal polynomial: 432*x^4 - 207*x^2 + 4.
%e A395466 0.142031526333085112689793906561431961141056652520154...
%t A395466 RealDigits[Sqrt[(69 - 11*Sqrt[33])/2]/12, 10, 120][[1]]
%o A395466 (PARI) sqrt((69 - 11*sqrt(33))/2)/12
%Y A395466 Cf. A395465, A395467, A395468, A395469, A395470, A395471, A395472.
